, commemorating as well as striking, rioting and rebelling; and it listens within the walls of a range of associations where it was a part of a way of life, inspiring, nurturing, though at times restrictive. It provides an opportunity to hear history as it happened.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aStudies in Imperialism 2017. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  aAnglophone world.  aAustralian exceptionalism.  aappropriation.  ahymn-singing.  aiconic songs.  aindigenous agency.  amusic-making . inter-colonial history.  amusical culture.  apolitical culture.  asound of music.  asounds of liberty.  atransnational history.  atravelling activists.  awhite colonizers.1 aBowan, Kate, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPickering, Paul A., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aPickering, Paul A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2017 eBook-Packagez978311128281740uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152610622340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526106223423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526106223/original  a978-3-11-128281-7  Manchester University Press 2017 eBook-Packageb2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles